amazon.Title: Amazon
amazon.Copy: <p class="switch-off">The Peel Group had a vision to create a city within a city without the constraints of existing architecture or infrastructure. Over the past three years that vision has become MediaCityUK. MediaCityUK is designed specifically around the media industry. It&rsquo;s a concept that reflects the way the industry is moving, as the boundaries between &lsquo;new&rsquo; and &lsquo;old&rsquo; media become increasingly blurred. It is also one of Europe&rsquo;s biggest building projects with phase 1 covering more than 36 acres.</p><p class="switch-off">&nbsp;</p><p class="switch-off">Since the construction team arrived at Salford Quays in summer 2007 more than 7.3 million man hours have been spent on site. Work was completed in 2011 following input from nearly 2,000 people. Such a big development has had a massive effect on the local skyline, but together with the management contractor, Bovis Lend Lease, the Peel Group has also helped the community feel the economic benefits of the build process. To date, more than &pound;200m of work has been awarded to Manchester contractors, including &pound;92m to Salford- based firms.</p><p class="switch-off">&nbsp;</p><p align="LEFT">As part of the construction of MediaCityUK there were a large number of new roofs that required waterproofing. Sika Liquid Plastics&nbsp;had the opportunity to create specifications for several of the projects within the development and successfully won buildings B and C (which are now used by the BBC), and the studios and residential towers.</p><p align="LEFT">&nbsp;</p><p>As with any major new construction there were many challenges faced by the roofing contractors, such as working around other trades and ensuring new roofs are waterproofed on schedule.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sika Liquid Plastics produces a range of complete roof systems, and several options were utilised on MediaCityUK. Building C levels 6 and 7 have an inverted roof system with level 7 also having a Decothane Delta 25 warm roof system installed on the upstands. In addition the timber canopy on this level was waterproofed with Decothane Delta 25. Building B and the studios had an Inverted Roof System installed which includes a root resistant version of Decothane &ndash; Sika Liquid Plastics market leading liquid applied roofing membrane.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Finally the residential towers had a Cold Fusion Bonded Built-Up Roof System with a tapered insulation scheme and a Decothane Delta 25 waterproofing membrane.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Decothane is a liquid applied membrane that cures to provide completely seamless waterproof protection. It can easily accommodate any complex detail areas on the roof to provide total encapsulation and no risk of leaks. Because it is cold applied, the roofing contractors can work safely alongside other trades without causing any danger due to hot works. The Inverted Roof System is guaranteed to last for 25 years with a BBA durability statement that suggests it may last the lifetime of the building. Furthermore, because the systems were installed by Sika Liquid Plastics&nbsp;Quality Assured Contractors, a Single Point Guarantee could be issued covering materials and labour for complete peace of mind.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Throughout the project Sika Liquid Plastics&nbsp;Technical Field Services and Technical Customer Services Teams were on hand to provide comprehensive support. This began at the pre-start stage with attendance at design meetings. This helped our team develop a bespoke specification including detail drawings and any necessary calculations. During the works the local Technical Field Manager attended site regularly to provide inspection reports for the client and to sign off completed roof areas as each stage was completed. As a result the client knew when a roof could be handed over to other trades and the progress of the works could be closely monitored to ensure schedules and quality of work was maintained.</p>
amazon.Contractor: Bovis Lend Lease, Prater and 5M (UK) Ltd.

liebherr.Title: Liebherr
liebherr.Copy: <p>Manchester airport is one of the world&rsquo;s principal airports and as such handles approximately 20 million passengers every year. Terminal 1 consists of 107 check-in desks, 24 pier served aircraft stands, 18 air bridges, restaurants and a shopping mall. When re-roofing a project of this magnitude, everything has to be carried out without interference to the smooth operation of the Airport&rsquo;s commerce and functionality.<br /><br />There were two phases of works required at Terminal 1, the first being a series of asphalt roofs that had failed. The main problem here was the presence of a great deal of plant equipment, which meant that the only system that could successfully waterproof the area would be a liquid applied system. Furthermore the majority of roof areas are regularly trafficked by workmen, therefore once the waterproofing&nbsp;was&nbsp;complete it needed to be overlaid with paving stones to create safe walkways.<br /><br />A Decothane Omega 15 system from Sika Liquid Plastics was specified and applied by a member of its Quality Assured Contractor programme - Weatherproofing Advisors. Prior to the waterproofing&nbsp;being&nbsp;applied, the existing paving stones were lifted and the underlying asphalt surfaces were power washed to ensure a clean substrate was available. Similar preparation was also carried out on roof areas with loose laid insulation being re-used once the new waterproofing system had been installed. For phase two &ndash; the control tower &ndash; red Decothane was used to highlight walkway areas and a Skid Inhibiting Agent was added to aid slip resistance.<br /><br />Decothane is easily applied around detail areas because of its liquid formulation and the curing process is moisture triggered so it cures quickly even in damp environments. This meant that the walkways could be rapidly returned to service to ensure minimum disruption to everyday operations. Furthermore it is completely cold applied thus eliminating the risk of fire often associated with using hot works. The completed systems are guaranteed to last for at least 15 years but as many areas are protected with pavers or insulation, these can be expected to outlive their guaranteed lives.</p>
